<answer>
    {Solution}
    The binomial probability formula is given by P(X = k) = \binom{n}{k}p^k(1-p)^{n-k}, where n is the number of trials, k is the number of successes, and p is the probability of success on a single trial.
    In this case, n = 3 (since we are considering three children), p = \dfrac{1}{2} (since the probability of a boy or a girl is equally likely), and k can be either 1 or 2 (since we want at least one boy and one girl).
    Therefore, the probability of having at least one boy and one girl is given by P(X = 1) + P(X = 2).
    P(X = 1) = \binom{3}{1}(\dfrac{1}{2})^1(\dfrac{1}{2})^2 = 3(\dfrac{1}{2})(\dfrac{1}{4}) = \dfrac{3}{8}
    P(X = 2) = \binom{3}{2}(\dfrac{1}{2})^2(\dfrac{1}{2})^1 = 3(\dfrac{1}{4})(\dfrac{1}{2}) = \dfrac{3}{8}
    Therefore, the probability of having at least one boy and one girl is:
    P(X = 1) + P(X = 2) = \dfrac{3}{8} + \dfrac{3}{8} = \dfrac{3}{4}
    The answer is $\boxed{\dfrac{3}{4}}$.

